post_text:
After much deliberation and consultation with the Snohomish County Health District and collaboration with our labor unions, we are announcing that Monroe School District will start the 2020-21 school year with distance learning on Wednesday, September 9, 2020. It is our ultimate goal to have all students in our buildings as soon as it can be safely done. Detailed information will be shared in the coming weeks to assist with this transition. MSD families, please keep an eye on your email and the district website for updates.

We know there are many questions and we will not be responding to questions on social media. Instead, please email them to: communications@monroe.wednet.edu. This will allow us to get the questions to the correct Monroe team member and compile common questions for an FAQ on the website.

Read more here:
https://www.monroe.wednet.edu/about/news/new-page/~post/msd-2020-21-school-year-to-start-with-distance-learning-20200731

Here is a peek into the in-person, drive through graduation that the amazing staff at Monroe High School Monroe, WA pulled off for the Class of 2020!

For two days MHS staff lined the parking lot to cheer on the graduates as they picked up their diplomas, crossed the stage and turned their tassels. Families were queued to the perfect spot to capture the moment on ALL the devices, as you can see in the video. In addition, a professional photographer and videographer were on hand to capture the moment for families and those videos and pictures will be shared directly to families in the coming weeks.

Congratulations MHS #Classof2020, we are proud of you!
#WeAreMSD #GoBearcats

https://youtu.be/AzSRhCTPbrw

Snohomish County Fire District 7
June 21 at 11:19 PM ·

Congrats to all students who were able to finish the school year while being faced with something you’ve never dealt with before! (Hats off everyone who supported our students during this time!) Welcome to summer fun! ☀️

Over the last 13 weeks we have taught a Firefighter Homeschool Lesson every Tuesday! Our Music Lesson was postponed, but we couldn’t let it go! (We will also have 1 more lesson this Thursday to wrap up the Homeschool Lessons!)

Join us this WEDNESDAY, June 24th for a FUN firefighter music lesson! Members of the Snohomish County Firefighters Pipes & Drums will join us to help teach the lesson!

Bring a pot and wooden spoon to the lesson and join in the fun!

**Free summer meals ended on August 31st. Meals will resume on September 9th. Be on the lookout for an announcement with times and locations.**

Even though tomorrow is the last day of school, we are continuing our free meal service at all of our elementary schools and designated bus meal delivery locations through June 30!

Beginning July 1st, grab and go lunches will only be available at Frank Wagner Elementary and Fryelands Elementary from 11:00-12:00, and at Maltby Elementary from 12:30-1:00 Monday-Friday. There will be no meal service on Friday, July 3rd.

Food assistance is available for families that qualify for free or reduced lunch! Learn more at: https://medium.com/@waOSPI/what-is-pandemic-ebt-a7a086fcaf94

Because schools have been closed due to COVID-19, families in Washington state will soon have food benefits available to them to help buy groceries while children have been home from school.

Called Pandemic EBT, or P-EBT, these food benefits are available to families with children who are eligible for schools’ free or reduced-price meal programs. The Public Charge rule does not apply to P-EBT benefits and will not impact immigration status.

The countdown is on! Two weeks left of school (one week for seniors)! Our official last day of school is June 19.

We are still awaiting reopening guidance from OSPI on what school will look like in the fall. Once we receive that guidance, we will formulate a committee (staff, parents, students) to review it and come up with an individual district plan and timeline. We will keep you posted as more information is released.

Once we receive that guidance, we will formulate a committee (staff, parents, students) to review it and come up with an individual district plan and timeline. We will keep you posted as more information is released.

This morning, we learned of an appalling series of postings on social media overnight involving some individuals who are also students of the District. The District is still reviewing the information provided but, without reservation, I can convey that hate speech and viewpoints supporting such speech do not reflect the values of the Monroe School District. We do not, and will not, stand-by acts, messages, or tolerance of inequality from our students or our employees."
Read the letter in full from Superintendent Dr. Justin Blasko: https://bit.ly/2XKYPbG

Friendly reminder: our schools will be closed Friday, May 22 and Monday, May 25 in observance of Memorial Day. All school offices and the district office will be closed.

MEMORIAL DAY WEEKEND FOOD SERVICE
To allow our fabulous food service employees to take the pre-arranged 4-day Memorial Day weekend off, meals for Thursday (5/21), Friday (5/22), and Monday (5/25) will be distributed at all five elementary schools and bus stops on Thursday, May 21st only. Please bring a big bag, backpack or enough hands to carry home the extra food! There will be no food service on 5/22 and 5/25.

We hope you enjoy the long weekend!

Kindergarten registration for the 2020-21 school year is available online!

If you have a child who will be 5 years old by August 31, 2020, please register for kindergarten now! In order to appropriately staff our kindergarten classes for next year, we need incoming kindergarten students to enroll as soon as possible.

We know that many families are having difficulties obtaining immunization records during this difficult time, so if you are not able to register online at this time due to that, please call your local school and let them know you plan to register your child for next year.

Learn more here: https://www.monroe.wednet.edu/about/register-for-school/kindergarten-registration

Although he has been part of the Monroe School District team for some time, Dr. Justin Blasko wanted to take a few minutes to virtually introduce himself as he steps into the role of superintendent.

"I am truly honored to be stepping into the role of superintendent even though it is a bit earlier than originally planned. While no one could have predicted the events that have unfolded recently, I am confident that our strong and dedicated teams will continue to provide our students and community with unwavering support and care during this challenging time." -Dr. Justin Blasko

The Monroe School District free meal service is continuing during spring break and throughout the extent of Governor Inslee’s Executive Order for Washington residents to stay at home. The provision of meals to children is considered an “essential operation” and therefore is permitted to continue. Thank you to our staff who continue to make sure our students are taken care of!

Free grab and go meals will continue to be handed out from 11:30-1:30 Monday through Friday at all five elementary schools and meal deliveries will continue to designated locations: https://www.monroe.wednet.edu/departments/health-services/coronavirus/meals-for-students

When picking up meals, we urge all students and families to please maintain social distancing to protect themselves and our community from further spreading of the COVID-19 virus. Thank you!

Monroe Public Schools Foundation
March 23 at 3:16 PM ·

Our All in for Kids Dinner and Benefit has moved to a virtual auction coming up this week Friday, March 27 thru Saturday, March 28. Although our event has changed, our need to support our students, teachers and staff is greater than ever. Register online for our auction at https://monroeps2020allinforkids.ggo.bid/

Even with school closed we are making a difference. Children are continuing to learn with books from our partnership with the Monroe Library and Cat Tales. Efforts are underway to support online learning for those without access. We’ve connected with school leaders to ensure they are able to respond to families in need.

Our work must continue. For that reason, we have taken all the generous auction donations ONLINE! We are still All in for Kids, we need YOU now more than ever.

post_text:
All schools in Monroe School District will be closed Thursday, March 5th. It is important to know there are no confirmed cases of coronavirus in the Monroe School District at this time. We will be using tomorrow to clean buildings and buses and give our staff contingency planning time. There will be no out-of-district transportation. All after school and evening activities and events are also canceled, including kindergarten information night.

All staff should report to work as usual on Thursday, March 5th unless you are ill. Please contact your healthcare provider for their recommendations on reporting to work if you fall into one of the higher risk categories as indicated by the Washington State Department of Health:

-Over 60 years of age
-With underlying health conditions including heart disease, lung disease, or diabetes
-With weakened immune systems
-Who are pregnant

Employees not reporting to work will need to use sick leave. We will update you later today regarding Friday’s schedule.

Congratulations to Hidden River Middle School's Director of Bands, Suzanne Chickering, for being named KRKO-AM 1380 radio's February Educator of the Month!

Nominated by Aurora, here is what she had to say about Ms. Chickering, "With a love for band and the motivation to keep students involved, this teacher has gone above and beyond standards. Mrs. Chickering has been a teacher at Hidden River Middle School for quite a while, she has always had the motivation to encourage kids to find their dream instrument, stay involved in band and learn instruments that aren't common. Overall, this teacher works day in and day out with students to assure that they have an instrument to take home that is reasonable for the families, and can enjoy such a wonderful art."

#WeAreMSD #HRMSHawks

Grab your popcorn and soda! The Monroe Community Coalition and Galaxy 12 Theatre Monroe are pleased to invite you to a free Night At the Movies on Monday, March 30th, featuring Screenagers Next Chapter: Uncovering Skills for Stress and Resilience!

Tickets are limited and typically go fast!

Register For Your Ticket Now: https://screenagersnextchapter_mcc2020.eventbrite.com

Doors open at 6:15, movie starts promptly at 7pm

It's been two years since the Coalition showed the first Screenagers and high stress, anxiety and depression are still experienced by thousands of young people in Monroe. Screenagers Next Chapter follows physician and filmmaker Delaney Ruston as she discovers solutions for improving our teen's well-being in the digital age.

Please join us to learn about strategies and tools you can use to foster mental wellness in youth!

Congrats to Scott Darrow, the new @MTownBearcats head football coach!
#WeAreMSD #GoBearcats
shared_text:
Monroe High School Monroe, WA
February 25 at 9:56 AM ·

Monroe High School is pleased to announce they've completed the hiring process and selected Scott Darrow as the next head football coach. Darrow completed his 15th year as assistant coach of MHS football this season.

"I'm thrilled to have Scott be the next head football coach at Monroe High School," said Jeannette Siemers, MHS Athletic Director. "He loves these kids. He loves this town and he loves this program. Scott was chosen because of his unique and long-term ties to the MHS and MHS Football community. He is the perfect candidate who already has established relationships with our student-athletes and I am confident that he will usher in a new era of Bearcat Football to continue to grow our program. I know our kids are excited to have Coach Darrow take over the reins too. It's a great day to be a Bearcat!"

Read more here: https://www.monroe.wednet.edu/about/news/new-page/~post/monroe-high-school-announces-hiring-of-scott-darrow-as-head-football-coach-20200214
#GoBearcats

post_text:
Over the next week, we will be sharing answers to some of the frequently asked questions we have received about the renewal technology levy that is currently on the ballot.

Q: Didn’t the Capital Projects Bond to renovate schools that was passed in 2015 include technology?

A: School district bonds approved by voters can ONLY be used to purchase property for schools, construct new schools, or modernize existing schools. Through funding from the 2015 bond, we were able to modernize Park Place Middle School, Salem Woods Elementary, Frank Wagner Elementary, and Hidden River Middle School. The modernization of these schools included technology such as electronic locks and programming, security systems and wireless network infrastructure. The bond did not pay for classroom presentation systems, student devices, or staff computing devices. Funding for those technologies came from the Technology Levy that was passed in 2014.

Have more questions? Submit them here: https://www.monroe.wednet.edu/community/bonds-levies/2020-technology-levy/technology-levy-renewal-faqs

#MSDTechLevy2020

The Washington Interscholastic Activities Association (WIAA) has announced the state’s high school athletic classifications for the 2020-24 cycle. As announced in early January, all Monroe High School athletic teams will be classified as 3A beginning in the fall of 2020.

The one sport Wesco has finalized division alignments for is football, which will include a three-division setup with a Wesco 4A, Wesco 3A North and Wesco 3A South.

Monroe will compete in Wesco 3A South along with Edmonds-Woodway, Lynnwood, Meadowdale, Mountlake Terrace, Shorecrest, and Snohomish. This does not include non-league games.

More details in the Everett Herald: https://bit.ly/2RXcaLb
#WeAreMSD #GoBearcats

Did you know that the Technology Levy approved by Monroe voters in 2014 is set to expire this year?

The renewal of this Technology Levy is on this February's Special Election ballot. Funding from this levy would allow us to keep technology for students current with industry standards and continue to provide training to our staff in integrating 21st century technology skills into classroom instruction. This levy would not be a new tax, it would be a renewal of what was previously approved in 2014.

Learn more, get answers to frequently asked questions, and submit your own questions here: https://www.monroe.wednet.edu/community/bonds-levies/2020-technology-levy

post_text:
January is School Board appreciation month! MSD's Board of Directors is comprised of five community members and is commonly referred to as the School Board. The board members are elected by local voters according to the geographical district in which they live to ensure representation from across the 82 square miles of our service area. Each Director serves a term of four years and must run for re-election once the term is up. We are thankful for our committed and hard-working board!

https://www.monroe.wednet.edu/about/school-board
#WeAreMSD #schoolboardmonth

Students and Staff at Hidden River Middle School were all smiles when they returned to school this week as the addition to their school was open! The new wing features a new commons/cafeteria, kitchen, two science classrooms, two general classrooms, a visual arts classroom, and a STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering and Math) lab.

The construction project also features a new football/soccer field and a baseball field, both with synthetic turf. Even during the brisk weather, students were out enjoying the fields.

Be on the lookout for the official ribbon-cutting ceremony and grand opening later this year when the project is 100% completed.
#WeAreMSD #2015BondUpdate #ThankYouVoters

The Monroe School District Start Time Advisory Committee, made up of parents, staff and students, would like your feedback to help guide their work. The survey was sent via email to all Monroe School District families, staff and students. Survey participation is optional.

The Start Time Advisory Committee is working to evaluate school start & dismissal times. The committee will be engaged in exploring a variety of options related to start times, gathering community input and potentially making recommendations for change to the school board, if deemed necessary.

The survey will close on January 7, 2020: https://bit.ly/2LL9Wwd

*Note: We ask that you please share your input and comments on the survey only. Comments posted here will not be accepted. Thank you.

So many fun Thanksgiving-themed learning activities going on in our schools this week! Third grade students at Salem Woods Elementary learned all about the time-honored Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade and all of the training that goes into being a balloon handler in the parade. They then designed and created their own balloon characters and showcased their creations by parading them around the school.

Interested in learning more about being a balloon handler in the Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade? Try reading the incredible picture book "Balloons Over Broadway: The True Story of the Puppeteer of Macy's Parade."
#WeAreMSD #SWE

High school athletic teams in Washington are categorized (4A, 3A, 2A, etc) by the WIAA based on the school's average student enrollment. Walking past the Park Place Middle School library this week you may have noticed a construction hat, squeezable hearts, video games or a skeleton. What was going on in there? It was the STEM Like ME! event!

STEM Like ME! empowers teachers to introduce STEM professionals into the classroom to educate students about careers options that are available to them: https://washingtonstem.org/stem-like-me-introduces-students-to-real-stem/.

Thank you Snohomish STEM for partnering with us to help make this event a reality and to all the businesses that presented to our students: EvergreenHealth Monroe, Stage 2 Studios, Providence Health & Services, Northwest Washington, City of Monroe, WA, Core Design, Farmer Frog Horticulture and Abbott Construction.
#WeAreMSD #STEMLikeME

post_text:
Yesterday morning was a dream come true for the Frank Wagner Elementary School Wildcats! Thanks to a personal invite from music teacher Bobbi Ann George, students started their day with world-renowned ukelele player Jake Shimabukuro. When Bobbie Ann saw Shimabukuro was touring in the area she invited him to stop by Frank Wagner and he said yes!

Shimabukuro performed songs, taught students about the ukelele and encouraged the students to find their passion in life, follow it and stay drug free.

You could see how excited Frank Wagner students were to practice all that they had learned on their ukeleles in music class. Thanks to a $6K Music Matters grant from Music Aid Northwest and Washington Music Educators Association (WMEA), more ukeleles are on the way to Frank Wagner!

Thank you Everett Herald for capturing this awesome event: https://www.heraldnet.com/news/world-renowned-ukelele-player-wows-frank-wagner-elementary/
#WeAreMSD

ONE more day until #FirstDayMonroe! Two things you can do today to help prepare for a successful start to the school year:

PRACTICE GETTING UP ON TIME
Prepare for school by setting the alarm and waking the family up on time. Being at school on time every day is important for staying on track academically.

GET YOUR SMILES READY
When you take your first day of school photos share them online and use #FirstDayMonroe or send them to communications@monroe.wednet.edu. We can't wait to all of the great back to school photos!

Need help? Check out our back to school checklist found on our website: https://bit.ly/2NFOOsN

post_text:
TWO more days until #FirstDayMonroe! Two things you can do today to help prepare for a successful start to the school year:

SIGN UP TO RECEIVE TEXT MESSAGES
Wondering why other families are getting helpful text messages from the district and you are not? The district text message service is an 'opt-in' service. You can participate in the free service by sending a text message of "Y" or "Yes" to our district's short code number, 67587. Our text message system is compliant with the Student Privacy Pledge so you can rest assured that your information is safe and will never be given or sold to anyone.

FOLLOW US ON SOCIAL MEDIA
Follow Monroe School District (@monroewaschools) on Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram. Monroe School District utilizes social media as a means of enhancing existing communication strategies and celebrating student, staff and school achievements.

Need help? Check out our back to school checklist found on our website: https://bit.ly/2NFOOsN
#WeAreMSD

post_text:
For our next stop, let's head back up to Monroe High School Monroe, WA to check out the progress on the football field. The football/soccer field synthetic turf is being replaced featuring a new center field logo and Lacrosse field markings for community use. The rubber track will also be resurfaced and there will be a Javelin runway lane and ball control netting so multiple groups/sports can practice simultaneously.

Also at MHS, thank you to the combined effort of the Monroe Public Schools Foundation and the 2015 Capital Projects Bond, new stage lights are going in at the performing arts center (PAC). The new LED lights will utilize less power and feature a new light board where changes can be made with a touch of a button!
#WeAreMSD #2015BondUpdate

Register your kids online.

The two closest participating bowling alleys are in the Everett area: Evergreen Lanes & Glacier Lanes

Next week we will be asking families to let us know what they think through a survey developed by the Center of Educational Effectiveness. The survey may be filled out online or via a paper copy from the main office. This important survey will be anonymous and will only take about 10 minutes to complete. The survey will be open from Monday, June 3 to Friday, June 14.

In addition to feedback from our families, we also want to hear from our students. Therefore, we will be asking students in grades 4-12 to complete a similar survey during the school day between June 3-14. This survey will be administered by school staff.

We value your input as we strive to continue to improve our school. Thank you in advance for your important feedback!

post_text:
This spring a group of our elementary students had the opportunity to raise butterflies! To start, each student had a caterpillar at their desk to care for and observe. The caterpillars stayed on their desks until they were in the chrysalis stage. At that point, they moved into large nets where they would work hard to become butterflies.

The excited students practiced their patience during the entire process and were sure to write down their observations in great detail during each stage as the caterpillar transformed into a butterfly.

When release day arrived, the students carefully took the butterflies out to the field, gathered in a circle and waiting quietly for them to fly away. Giggles filled the circle when the butterflies were a little shy and needed a bit of encouragement to take flight. When they were finally ready, some butterflies took to the sky while others landed on nearby grass, and to much delight, on several students.

What an amazing opportunity for our students. Look to the skies, you may see some of their butterflies!
#WeAreMSD

Monroe High School Monroe, WA senior Hannah Lee is the first student from MHS to finish in the top three in a percussion category at state AND she placed in two of the categories! She finished 3rd in both the mallet and timpani divisions. MHS also had a trombone choir go to State as well as Zachary Reule on snare drum and Ethan Dunn on tuba.

All students that participated at state won their category at the Mount Pilchuck Music Educator's Association regional solo contest in February.

Way to go @MTownBearcats, you make us #proudtobeinMSD!
#WeAreMSD #GoBearcats

Shout out to the Monroe High School Monroe, WA Spring musical Curtains for receiving The 5th Avenue Theatre Award nominations for Outstanding Music Direction, Outstanding Orchestra, Outstanding Performance by an Actor in a Leading Role (Spencer Langston as Cioffi), and an Honorable Mention for Outstanding Performance by a Chorus.

According to the, 5th Avenue Theatre, the award program allow musical theater students from across Washington State to meet, celebrate, and honor the exceptional musical theater productions presented during the 2018/19 school year. This was a record breaking year with 128 productions at 106 schools with more than 11,000 participating students submitted for evaluation.

You can see all the nominees here: https://bit.ly/2YHdC64. The award ceremony is scheduled for June 3rd. Best of luck to all!
#WeAreMSD

A huge congratulations to Chain Lake Elementary on recently being named as a Washington State Recognized School!

The Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction, State Board of Education, and Educational Opportunity Gap Oversight and Accountability Committee have created a new system of recognizing and celebrating schools’ achievement on the Washington School Improvement Framework (WSIF) measures.

Recognized schools measure within the top 20 percent on the WSIF measures and are making significant progress closing gaps among student groups that have been identified for support.

Learn more here: http://sbe.wa.gov/our-work/accountability/2017-2018-state-recognized-schools?fbclid=IwAR29VGo9SqDXukql25MX1MmbGO9CLhoBEfHsoUGAVUT-379o0aVAo57lWLs

ICYMI: Monroe High School Monroe, WA students attended the State Ensemble Contest for Vocal and Instrumental groups at Central Washington University in late April.

At State, groups could compete in six vocal ensemble categories and six instrumental categories. MHS had three vocal ensembles competing in the categories for Large Mixed Ensemble, Small Mixed Ensemble, and Small Tenor/Baritone/Bass Ensemble.

After receiving the results, Monroe's Tenor/Baritone/Bass Quartet, Collin the Boys, placed 3rd in the State! Only 11 high schools received a trophy for placing at State this year, and MHS is very proud to be one of the schools awarded. Congrats!
#WeAreMSD #GoBearcats

shared_text:
City of Monroe, WA
April 26, 2019 at 2:58 PM ·

Thank you to everyone who came to celebrate Arbor Day & Earth Day and helped us plant a tree today! Our guests included: Monroe City Council member Kirk Scarboro. Park Board Members Tami Kinney, Ron Petrick and Jesse Robinson. Planning Commission Members Heather Rousey and Kyle Fisher. Kirsten Lints of Washington Community Forestry Council and State Department of Natural Resources. Principal Jeff Presley, Mrs. Hehn and her 3rd grade students of Fryelands Elementary School. Thanks to the Monroe Park Board & Historical Society for their work on our Heritage Trees program and to the landowners for sharing the stories of their magnificent trees. Then a big thank you to Monroe Garden Club for donating the beautiful Red Maple, we can't wait to see it grow in the years to come.

#arborday #earthday #laketye #plantatree #monroe

ICYMI: Sky Valley Education Center hosted Monday's School Board and while on campus the School Board Directors were able to visit the student Art-Science Showcase happening that evening.

The Showcase featured art exhibits, robotics, a star lab, a working trebuchet, flora and fauna, escape rooms, sewing exhibits, wood crafts, STEM projects, and so much more! The work on display was inspiring and a majority were interactive. In the robotics room, each exhibit was required to be a game which entertained guests of all ages.

If you weren't able to make it to the year's Showcase, be sure to follow the Sky Valley Education Center page for updates on next year's event.
#WeAreMSD #SVEC

It was all smiles despite the rain at Fryelands Elementary today! Students were given the opportunity to celebrate Earth Day (Pacific Northwest style with hoodies and umbrellas) in the Nature Park on campus. With help from the Fryelands PTA students helped prep and plant the raised garden beds, line the trail in the park with bark, plant a seed to take home, go on a scavenger hunt, and even peek in on some bird eggs in one of the birdhouses. What a great way to celebrate Earth Day!
#WeAreMSD

As a freshman last season, Hannah Ganashamoorthy shattered Monroe High School track records and collected three top-three track state medals in a sensational beginning to her prep career.

Ganashamoorthy’s personal-best mark of 20-2 in the long jump last season ranked 16th in the nation and was the best overall mark in the state by a foot.

After her exceptional freshman campaign, even more greatness could be in store for the Monroe phenom this spring. We can't wait to see what she accomplishes this season!

See the MHS girls' track meet schedule here: http://www.wescoathletics.com/index.php?pid=0.3.30.16.320

Read the full Everett Herald article here: https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/track-and-field-season-preview-five-storylines-to-watch/

All before and after school activities are cancelled as well. We know this is not ideal for families and we apologize for this unfortunate and unusual circumstance.

post_text:
Schools will open two hours late tomorrow Monday, February 11. No out of district transportation. No morning preschool. Buses will be on snow routes.

Our drivers have been out evaluating road conditions all afternoon and while much of the snow and ice has melted on the main roadways, many of the back roads throughout our district are still covered in compact snow and ice. With freezing temperatures again predicted overnight, we will be delaying the start of school by two hours to wait for daylight to provide safer driving conditions in the morning.

Our drivers will be out again tomorrow morning around 5 a.m. to evaluate conditions and if a change is necessary, we will notify families at that time.

post_text:
Friday, Feb. 8: Modified Early Release for All Schools
As we turn our attention to Friday's forecast, it is clear that more snow is likely coming and the winds will be picking up as well. With the amount of snow expected, we are being proactive in our planning for the safety of our students and staff. We will have a modified early release schedule on Friday, February 8, 2019. We will be starting at regular time. Elementary school will release at noon. Middle and High School will release at 11:00 am. School lunches will be provided. Middle and High School lunches will be a grab and go lunch.

-All WIAA athletic and music events will be communicated separately.
-All other after-school and evening activities across the District will be cancelled.
-All a.m./p.m. buses will be on snow routes.
-No out-of-district transportation.
-No zero-period classes.

-If your stop is listed, the modified pick up location is listed next to it with the pick up time. Please add two hours to the listed pick up time.

- If your regular bus stop is NOT listed, that means your bus will still pick you up at your regular stop, but two hours later than the regular time. Please note that pick up times may be affected by road conditions.

- Shuttle and transfer buses will still operate as normal, but two hours later than normal.

- Middle and high schools will begin at 9:50 a.m. and elementary schools will begin at 10:55 a.m.

-We will notify families later in the day whether afternoon buses will be operating on snow routes or returning to their regular routes.

-Please send your students to school dressed in warm layers!

Our crews have been out driving the roads our buses travel and checking school parking lot conditions since early this morning. While there is ice in spots on some of the back roads, the majority of the roads are clear and dry. Therefore, we are staying with the decision to delay the start of school by two hours and have our buses running on snow routes.

Please evaluate the road conditions in your neighborhood and use parental discretion in how your student is transported to school. Be safe and dress warm!
text:
Our crews have been out driving the roads our buses travel and checking school parking lot conditions since early this morning. While there is ice in spots on some of the back roads, the majority of the roads are clear and dry. Therefore, we are staying with the decision to delay the start of school by two hours and have our buses running on snow routes.

Please evaluate the road conditions in your neighborhood and use parental discretion in how your student is transported to school. Be safe and dress warm!

Schools will open two hours late tomorrow Wednesday, February 6. Buses will be on snow routes. No out of district transportation. No morning preschool.

Our drivers have been out evaluating road conditions all afternoon and while much of the snow and ice has melted on the main roadways, many of the back roads throughout our district are still covered in compact snow and ice. With freezing temperatures again predicted overnight, we will be delaying the start of school by two hours to wait for daylight to provide safer driving conditions in the morning.

Our drivers will be out again tomorrow morning around 5 a.m. to evaluate conditions and if a change is necessary, we will notify families at that time.

Students from Leaders in Learning High School had the opportunity to attend a special performance of "Dear Evan Hansen," a Broadway musical now playing at the Paramount in Seattle. The plot of the musical centers around teen suicide and its implications to a high school community.

Prior to the viewing, students listened to the song, "You Will Be Found," from the musical and created an art project (poem, song, artwork, etc.) that focused on the hardships of being a teen. One of our incredible Leaders in Learning student's project is featured in this Komo 4 news story. Way to go, Davin! #WeAreMSD

post_text:
What a fun learning opportunity from Pure Food Kids for our students at Chain Lake Elementary School!
#WeAreMSD #BeechersCheese #PureFoodKids
shared_text:
Chain Lake Elementary School is with Tamara Broughton Krache.
January 22, 2019 at 11:32 AM ·

A group of 4th graders completed the Beecher's Handmade Cheese Pure Food Kids workshop last week where they learned to be food detectives!

The Pure Food Kids workshop is a standards-aligned, nutrition education and cooking lesson that sparks curiosity about what’s really in the foods kids might eat. The students learned how to read nutrition labels and ingredient lists and how food companies are marketing to kids. To end the day, they learned to be chefs, cooking and eating tasty, nourishing veggie chili right in their classroom, complete with a chili cheers to celebrate! There were a lot of excited kids hoping to replicate the chili recipe at home for their families. What a fun learning opportunity for our students!
#BeechersCheese #PureFoodKids
